<p>For Bakersfield's hot-dry climate, high-efficiency air conditioning systems with SEER ratings of 16 or higher are recommended to handle the extreme heat while managing electricity costs. Two-stage or variable-speed compressors perform exceptionally well in desert conditions, providing better humidity control and more consistent temperatures. Since heating needs are minimal with only 2,707 heating degree days annually, a standard heat pump or high-efficiency air conditioner paired with a gas furnace offers the best value. Systems should be sized properly for the intense cooling loads - typically requiring 1 ton of cooling per 400-500 square feet rather than the standard 600 square feet used in milder climates. Evaporative coolers can supplement traditional systems during shoulder seasons, taking advantage of the low humidity to provide cost-effective cooling when temperatures are below 85¬∞F.</p>

